Epoch:1 | IDEA | Scientist0:Thought: The core challenge in calibrating Non-Parametric Significance Scores (NPSS) lies in the computational burden of randomization tests, which require repeated permutations to estimate null distributions. While existing methods rely on Monte Carlo approximations, they lack theoretical guarantees and scale poorly with sample size. Drawing inspiration from Papers 1–3—particularly their use of geometric reasoning, structured inequalities, and controlled relaxation of strict criteria—I aim to shift the paradigm from simulation-based calibration to analytical bounding via concentration inequalities over combinatorial structures. Specifically, Paper 1’s use of β-relaxation to guarantee existence of stable decision points suggests that relaxing exact permutation enumeration through structured deviation bounds could yield tractable yet rigorous lower bounds on significance thresholds. Meanwhile, Papers 2 and 3 demonstrate how minimal cardinal or structural information can drastically improve performance over purely ordinal models—paralleling our goal of replacing expensive sampling with targeted mathematical analysis. My key insight is that the permutation orbit of a test statistic under the null forms a structured metric space, enabling the application of deviation inequalities (e.g., McDiarmid-type) conditioned on group action symmetries. By analyzing worst-case deviations within orbits using Lipschitz properties and stabilizer subgroups, we can derive closed-form lower bounds for α′(N,α)—the calibrated significance level—without any sampling. This approach fundamentally differs from prior work by treating permutation symmetry as an analytic scaffold rather than a computational nuisance. It also introduces group-theoretic concentration tools to statistical ML, a novel intersection largely unexplored. Unlike asymptotic normality assumptions, our method remains valid for finite N and arbitrary test statistics, offering both speed and robustness.

