  "Idea": "This paper proposes a novel framework for fast calibration of Non-Parametric Significance Scores (NPSS) by deriving closed-form lower bounds for α′(N,α)—the effective significance threshold after multiple comparisons correction—through structured deviation inequalities over permutation orbits. Current NPSS calibration relies heavily on computationally intensive randomization tests that simulate the null distribution via repeated shuffling, becoming prohibitive for large-scale applications such as genomics, neuroimaging, or A/B testing at internet scale. Our approach eliminates this bottleneck by leveraging the inherent symmetry of permutation groups acting on data vectors to derive deterministic, finite-sample lower bounds on α′(N,α) using concentration inequalities tailored to group orbits. We introduce the concept of 'orbit-smoothness'—a measure of how much a test statistic changes under transpositions—and show that statistics with bounded orbit-smoothness satisfy McDiarmid-type inequalities even under dependent permutations. By decomposing the permutation group into cosets relative to stabilizer subgroups of observed data configurations, we derive tight deviation bounds that depend only on N, α, and intrinsic statistic properties (e.g., sensitivity to rank swaps). These bounds yield analytically tractable expressions for α′(N,α), enabling calibration in O(1) time post-analysis. Crucially, our method does not assume asymptotic normality or exchangeability beyond the null, making it suitable for complex dependencies and small samples. We further enhance tightness by incorporating thresholding mechanisms inspired by Paper 3’s approval sets, defining 'active orbits' where significant deviations are possible, thereby improving bound sharpness. The resulting framework enables real-time significance calibration in interactive data exploration and large-scale inference pipelines, reducing reliance on high-performance computing for statistical validation. Potential impact spans machine learning interpretability (e.g., SHAP value calibration), causal inference, and fairness auditing, where rapid, reliable p-value adjustment is essential.",
